gomodel:SYNGO_4053  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 4B: Application of NPY5R antagonist L-152,804, prevented NPY induced increase in the frequency of mIPSCs.\nFigure 4C-E: Application of another NPY5R antagonist CGP 71683 had a similar effect on the NPY induced increase in the frequency of mIPSCs. Neither L-152,804 nor CGP 71683 applied alone altered mIPSC frequency or amplitude. DMSO at the concentration used to dissolve the antagonists also did not alter the NPY-induced I-LTP.\nFigure 5A and C: Coapplication of NPY1R and NPY2R antagonists BIBP3236 (BIBP) and BIIE-0246 (BIIE) did not prevent NPY-induced increase in GABA release characterising the specific role of NPY5R in the process.\nFigure 5D-F: Application of NPY5R agonist induced a sustained increase in mIPSC frequency that mimicked the NPY-induced increase in spontaneous GABA release.\n\n11/01/2021 Dnyanada: The paper demonstrates the involvement of neuropeptide receptor NPY5R in the long-lasting increase in spontaneous GABA release.. Experimental description: Cerebella of 1-wk-old C57BL/6J mice were dissociated as described previously (Fiszman et al. 2005). Whole-cell patch-clamp recordings were made at 22°C from cultured granule cells in an extracellular solution (in mM: 145 NaCl, 3 KCl, 1 MgCl2, 2 CaCl2, 25 glucose, and 10 HEPES, pH 7.3). Granule cells were identified by their morphological characteristics and lack of spontaneous action potentials in cell-attached mode." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2021-01-18" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4053" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

